{
    "analysis": "The Executor loaded all telemetry files and returned a compact summary. Key facts: metric.csv has 325,376 rows spanning timestamps 1647840600..1647844200; 59 unique cmdb_id and 1,424 unique kpi_name. trace.csv has 36,316 rows spanning 1647842400..1647844200; 40 unique cmdb_id and ~200 unique trace_name. log.csv has 1,842 rows spanning 1647842400..1647844200; 31 unique cmdb_id and 2 log_name values. error_logs.csv is empty. The incident time window (2022-03-21 14:00–14:30 UTC+8) maps to timestamps 1647842400..1647844200 and is fully covered by trace and log data and partially by metric data (metric min timestamp is earlier). Next we must preprocess: identify which candidate components (pods/services/nodes from the allowed lists) actually appear in the telemetry and get per-component metric/trace/log coverage so we can compute global thresholds per component-KPI only for those present. This will narrow the search space for anomaly detection.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For each telemetry file (metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv) do the following and return compact aggregates only (limit rows to top 20):\n1) For the file, list the top 20 cmdb_id values by row count along with (row_count, number_of_unique_kpi_or_trace_or_log_names). Use kpi_name for metric.csv, trace_name for trace.csv, log_name for log.csv.\n2) Also return the total number of distinct kpi/trace/log names in that file.\nDo not print raw time series. Keep output terse (one row per cmdb_id with the three columns requested)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace interval extraction shows a broad set of services (frontend, adservice, checkoutservice, cartservice, recommendationservice, productcatalogservice, paymentservice, currencyservice, etc.) exhibiting sustained anomalous trace error_rate intervals starting at the incident window start (1647842400). Many error_rate series had P95==P5==0 so every in-window row was flagged; this indicates either true error conditions (non-zero error_rate would show) or that zero-values as thresholds caused all rows to be considered anomalous. Metric anomalies were concentrated on 'adservice' but were ambiguous because many KPIs were constant-valued. To separate the two distinct failures within the 14:00–14:30 window and localize root causes, we next need to inspect logs (error_count and row_count) for in-window increases or drops and resource-related metric KPIs (cpu/memory/io/network) for clear resource faults. Logs can quickly indicate which components experienced errors and the earliest error timestamps. If logs point to specific components and timestamps, we will then correlate with trace intervals and resource KPIs to determine root-cause reason (e.g., CPU spike, memory exhaustion, process termination, network issues, or disk I/O).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "On log.csv perform the following (return compact table, max 20 rows):\n1) Filter to the incident window: timestamp >= 1647842400 and timestamp <= 1647844200.\n2) For each cmdb_id where log_name == 'log.error_count', compute: total_rows_in_window, count_nonzero_error_rows (value>0), sum_error_count (sum of value), earliest_nonzero_error_ts (min timestamp where value>0) if any, and min/max value in-window. Return rows where count_nonzero_error_rows>0 sorted by count_nonzero_error_rows desc (top 20).\n3) Also, for log_name == 'log.row_count' compute for each cmdb_id: total_rows_in_window, min_row_count_in_window, max_row_count_in_window, earliest_timestamp_of_min_rows (for drops). Return top 20 cmdb_id entries sorted by (max_row_count_in_window - min_row_count_in_window) descending.\n4) Finally, confirm whether error_logs.csv contains any rows and, if so, return up to 20 sample rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message). Keep output terse and textual; do not print full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric KPI scan found many resource-related KPIs that reference 'container.node-6.*' (network transmit/receive, fs I/O, threads, iowaiting, etc.) and these KPIs appear across many containers (adservice-*, frontend-*, etc.). This strongly suggests node-6–level resource telemetry is relevant to the incidents. Trace anomalies span the entire window starting at 1647842400, while log.row_count drops concentrate near the window end (min timestamps frequently 1647844200). To determine whether node-6 exhibited resource faults that coincide with one or both failures, we should inspect node-6 related KPI series rigorously: compute global thresholds (P95/P5) using the full series, then extract consecutive anomalous intervals within the incident window for node-6 KPIs. This will tell us whether node-level resource faults started at 14:00 (1647842400), at ~14:30 (1647844200), or both.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metric.csv, select all KPI series whose kpi_name contains the substring 'node-6' (case-insensitive). For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) do: 1) compute global P95 and P5 using the full available series for that pair (do NOT pre-filter by time); 2) filter rows to the incident window timestamp >=1647842400 and <=1647844200; 3) mark in-window rows anomalous when value >= P95 OR value <= P5; 4) extract consecutive anomalous intervals (timestamps gap <=60s) and for each interval return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, interval_start_ts, interval_end_ts, interval_length_rows, max_value_in_interval, P95, P5. Return up to 20 interval rows sorted by interval_start_ts ascending. Keep output compact and textual."
}

